<h2>
    Essential Gear for Sockeye Salmon Fishing
</h2>
<p>
    Having the right gear can make all the difference between a successful fishing trip and a frustrating one. Sockeye salmon, while smaller than Chinook, are feisty fighters and require specialized equipment.
</p>
<h3>
    Rod and Reel
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rod:</strong> Medium-light to medium-action spinning or casting rod (8–10 feet long)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Reel:</strong> Spinning or baitcasting reel with a smooth drag system
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line:</strong> 10–15 lb test monofilament or braided line with fluorocarbon leader
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Tackle
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Hooks:</strong> Barbless hooks required in many areas (sizes 1/0 to 3/0)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Weights:</strong> Sliding sinkers or drop-shot weights to keep bait near the bottom
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Floats:</strong> When fishing from shore, adjustable slip floats help in managing depth
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Accessories
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Polarized sunglasses (to reduce glare and spot fish)
    </li>
    <li>
        Landing net with rubber mesh (to avoid injuring fish)
    </li>
    <li>
        Tackle box with swivels, split shot, and spare leaders
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Investing in durable, quality gear ensures better handling and increases your chances of landing sockeye in strong currents.
</p>
<h2>
    Best Bait and Lure Techniques
</h2>
<p>
    Sockeye salmon are known for their selective feeding habits. While they primarily stop feeding during their migration upstream, they’ll still strike out of instinct or irritation, which is why presentation matters.
</p>
<h3>
    Natural Baits
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Salmon roe (eggs):</strong> Cured eggs are extremely effective and widely used
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Sand shrimp:</strong> Especially productive in moving water
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Herring strips:</strong> Best when used with a slow troll near deeper pools
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Artificial Lures
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spinners:</strong> Blue Fox Vibrax, Mepps, and Rooster Tails in red, orange, or pink
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Plugs:</strong> Wiggle Warts and Kwikfish with scent attractants
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Spoons:</strong> Flutter spoons mimic small baitfish and attract strikes
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Fly Fishing Setups
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Popular on rivers like the Deschutes
    </li>
    <li>
        Use bead patterns or small streamers in reds, oranges, and purples
    </li>
    <li>
        Floating or sink-tip lines depending on water depth
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Applying scent to lures or bait can also boost success rates. Sockeye have a keen sense of smell, and adding a salmon egg or shrimp oil attractant can make your offering irresistible.
</p>
